<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-23T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-23T18:00:00-05:00" n="182" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d182">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5131/931a: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in France (<persName type="to">Edge</persName>)</hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-23T18:00:00-05:00">December 23, 1932—6
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>451. At press conference today a correspondent made inquiry as to the
                                status of the commercial treaty. I stated in reply “The negotiations
                                    <pb facs="0352" n="262" xml:id="pg_262"/> have not been broken
                                off, but in view of the urgency of satisfactorily disposing of more
                                important matters, the actual negotiations are for the present being
                                held in abeyance”.</p>
                            <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_SHL1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>